**Abstract:**
Working notes titled "The Question of God in The Plague" addressing theodicy and Camus's treatment of suffering. Distinguishes Christian faith from philosophical theism, arguing Christians don't lose faith in face of innocent suffering because God "came to suffer and die with us" (Claudel). Discusses faith as trust rather than proof, critiques Russell's argument as applicable only to philosophical theism, and argues atheism is also "a leap of faith" - neither atheism nor theism can be demonstratively justified. Notes the problem of evil is encountered from within already-existing belief or unbelief, not from neutral standpoint.

**AI Recommendation:** Keep in undated/notes - substantive philosophical working notes on Camus

